[2] Pakistan (Khyber Pakhtunkhwa): 2 new cases
Date: Sat 23 Nov 2019
Source: Urdu Point [edited]
https://www.urdupoint.com/en/pakistan/nih-confirms-two-new-cases-from-lakki-marwat-769245.html


The infuriated polio virus has left 2 more children disabled for life as National Institute of Health (NIH) Islamabad on Saturday [23 Nov 2019] notified new polio cases from Lakki Marwat and district Bannu, taking the total case count to 66 in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa in the current year [2019] so far.

One wild poliovirus has been isolated from the stool sample of a 3-month-old female of union council Beistkhel, Tehsil Sarai Naurang district, Lakki Marwat and 10-month-old male resident of UC JaniKhel Tehsil Wazir, district Bannu.

The epidemiological study of the children shows that the female child from Lakki Marwat was zero dose for essential immunization, and her SIAs history is under investigation, while the male child had [one dose] of essential immunization, and his SIAs history is under investigation.

In his comment on reporting of new polio cases from Lakki Marwat and district Bannu, coordinator EOC Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Abdul Baist said it was a matter of grave concern and indeed a sad day that 2 more children are left disabled by poliovirus.

He said it was unfortunate that polio cases have jumped to 66 in the province with 18 cases from Lakki Marwat and 50 from Bannu division only.

Despite the fact that vaccine is available to prevent children from the disease, parents were not vaccinating their children due to misconceptions and were totally responsible for the disability of the children.

He said the virus is "on fire" in southern districts of the province, especially in Bannu division, and is circulating in the environment, hitting any unvaccinated or immune-compromised child.

He added that the only viable solution of the problem is to vaccinate the child in every campaign, as only repeated doses can protect the child from permanent disability and stop virus circulation in the environment.

Abdul Basit appealed to parent not to pay attention to propaganda and rumors, adding that polio vaccine is completely safe and does not cause any harm upon administration.

[Byline: Fahad Shabbir]

